## Appendix C Proofs

This section proves the main theorem with some lemmas and propositions. Similar to the [25], we first prove that the Gram matrix \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}^{\infty}\) is independent of \(m\) and strictly positive definite, in Proposition C.3. Second, as \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}\left(\bm{w}\left(0\right),\bm{v}\left(0\right)\right)\) is the sample mean, Proposition C.4 shows that \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}\left(\bm{w}\left(0\right),\bm{v}\left(0\right)\right)\) is close to its expected value \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}^{\infty}\) with a high probability, if \(m\) is large enough. This implies that \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}\left(\bm{w}\left(0\right),\bm{v}\left(0\right)\right)\) is strictly positive definite with high probability. Then, we show that the initial loss is bounded with a high probability if \(m\) is large. This is because \(\bm{v}\left(0\right)\) has zero mean, which hinders the output of \(m\) variables to diverge as \(m\) increases. Finally, we prove that the Gram matrix \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}\left(\bm{w}\left(t\right),\bm{v}\left(t\right)\right)\) remains within a small neighborhood of the initial point, where it maintains its strict positive definiteness. The gradient flow converges within the neighborhood, as the smallest eigenvalue of \(\widehat{\bm{G}}_{\bm{v}}\) is distinct from zero, resulting in a rapid reduction of the loss.

